{"title":"What We Ride: Matthew’s Giant Revolt Advanced with GRX Di2","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/giant-revolt-grx-di2","date":1694099728000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/giant-revolt-grx-di2\">What We Ride: Matthew’s Giant Revolt Advanced with GRX Di2</a></p>\n\n<p>There’s nothing like riding a bike you love, and it feels obvious to say that time spent riding bikes you don’t love is time wasted. I love my Giant Revolt. Let me tell you why.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>I’m a big believer in matching a bike to the riding you actually do, not the riding you think you should be doing. While I enjoy epic mountain climbs and smooth Euro tarmac as much as the next rider, this kind of riding is a tiny percentage of what I actually do in a given year. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Riding past trees\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-15.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>I live in the Forest of Dean and my bread and butter is mixed-surface trundling that blends gravelly trails and tarmac, occasionally veering into the vanilla end of mountain biking, that is, within the limits of what I can ride on a machine with relatively narrow drop bars.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>My ideal bike for this falls near the speedier end of the gravel spectrum, something with <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/road-bike-geometry-handling\" target=\"_blank\">geometry</a> that isn’t a total handful on occasional singletrack, clearances for decent-sized tyres but with a reasonable turn of speed on the road. In short, something a whole lot like my Revolt.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/giant-revolt-advanced-pro-1-review\">Giant Revolt Advanced Pro 1 review</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-gravel-bike\">Best of the best gravel bikes 2023: Cyclist’s top-rated gravel and adventure bikes</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/what-is-a-gravel-bike\">What is a gravel bike? Everything you need to know</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Why the Revolt?</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Giant Revolt with GRX Di2\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-2.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Despite gravel being a mainstay of my riding, I haven’t had a proper gravel bike of my own for quite some time. My stout steel <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/genesis-croix-de-fer-30-review\" target=\"_blank\">Genesis Croix de Fer</a> has stood in and done a very passable job, but it’s more of a <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-touring-bike\" target=\"_blank\">touring bike</a> and lacks racy zing.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Hunt carbon wheel with Schwalbe tyre\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-8.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>I was hugely impressed by the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/giant-revolt-advanced-pro-1-review\" target=\"_blank\">Giant Revolt Advanced Pro</a> when I reviewed it as it seemed to do a bit of everything well, so a Revolt frameset felt like a natural choice for a build tailored to my whims. With a set of lovely Hunt 25 Carbon Gravel Race wheels (just 1,332g on my scales) and a <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/shimano-grx-di2-groupset-review\" target=\"_blank\">Shimano GRX Di2 groupset</a>, the bike weighs just under 9kg with pedals and cages.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Over-the-stem computer mount\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-6.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>That includes plush tyres (40mm front, 45mm rear), a nondescript Brand-X carbon bar (that’s the actual brand name), a <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/american-classic-tyres\" target=\"_blank\">Knog Oi Luxe bell</a>, and a funky little stem cap computer mount from F3 Cycling, which I chose over an out-front mount because the latter inevitably clashes with my trendy bar bag.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Compared to just a few years ago, the range of gearing options has exploded and it has never been easier to get really low gears on drop-bar bikes. SRAM arguably leads the way with its huge cassettes and <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/sram-groupsets-buyers-guide\" target=\"_blank\">groupsets that let you mix road and mountain bike components</a>, but I wanted a GRX 2× groupset bike because I like the ergonomics and performance.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>For all the popularity and minimalist appeal of 1×, I think there’s still a place for 2× drivetrains on gravel bikes, particularly one that’s going to spend a good amount of time on tarmac, where more closely spaced gears tend to matter more.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Giant Revolt with GRX Di2\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-11.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>That said, Shimano GRX Di2 isn’t designed to accommodate a cassette larger than 11-34, and I wanted properly easy gears at the low end. Shimano has historically been conservative with its specs and word on the street is there’s some leeway here, so I went ahead and built the bike with a Deore XT 11-40 mountain bike cassette and… it works. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>A disclaimer, though: Shimano isn’t going to be terribly sympathetic if your rear derailleur explodes or your hanger snaps because you’re running a component combo it hasn’t endorsed. Proceed at your own risk.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>To stop the 40-tooth sprocket clashing with the upper jockey wheel of the rear derailleur, I had to wind the B-screw in quite far (this pushes the derailleur away from the cassette). Shifting is consequently a touch less crisp than it should be and the indexing needs to be absolutely spot-on, but it works pretty well, and gives me a ludicrously spinny 31/40 low gear that feels like it’ll haul me up a vertical cliff.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Road-adjacent</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>You could make this a much rowdier bike – fit a dropper, some wacky flared bars, chunky mud-plugging tyres, etc – but that wasn’t the goal here.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Fast rolling tread on tyre\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-9.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>I love how much the Revolt manages to feel like a road bike, plus a bit more. Tyres are, of course, a huge part of this. Schwalbe’s G-One Bites were my first choice, but <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/author/sam-challis\" target=\"_blank\">tech ed Sam</a> convinced me to try the speedier G-One Rs, and they’re a new favourite. The low-profile tread isn’t just for show – it adds meaningful grip on a typical fire road surface as long as things aren’t too greasy – but it rolls so well on tarmac.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Riding in front of the Severn Bridge\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-16.jpg 1800w\" /><figcaption>Joseph Branston / Cyclist</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The do-everything bike is a fallacy, because everything is compromise. Good design is compromise. <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/best-gravel-gearing-how-to-get-lower-gears\" target=\"_blank\">Gearing is compromise</a>. <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/buyers-guide-the-best-gravel-bike-tyres\" target=\"_blank\">Tyre choice is compromise</a>. My fitness is a compromise. But truthfully if I could only have one bike it would look a lot like this.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Matthew’s Giant Revolt spec</h2>\n\n\n\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Frame</td><td>Advanced grade carbon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Fork</td><td>Advanced SL-grade carbon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Weight</td><td>8.7kg including pedals, cages, computer mount, bell, pump mount</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Groupset</td><td>Shimano GRX Di2 48/31 w/11-40 Deore XT cassette</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Wheels</td><td>Hunt Carbon Gravel Race 25</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Tyres</td><td>Schwalbe G-One R 700×40 front, 700×45 rear, tubeless</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Cockpit</td><td>Brand-X 400mm carbon bar, Bontrager 90mm alloy stem</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Seatpost</td><td>Giant D-Fuse SLR carbon</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Saddle</td><td>Giant Approach SL</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Pedals</td><td>Shimano XTR PD-M9000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n\t<td>Accessories</td><td>Knog Oi Luxe bell, F3 Form Mount OTS computer mount, Cannondale carbon cages</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n\n\n<h2>More splendid pictures</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-3-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Bike in front of the Severn Bridge\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/09/giant-revolt-grx-di2-3-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99